{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473391"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2393"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2393"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.04,0.73,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103624"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86041"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2823"},{"type":"tags","id":"3622"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1581"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10720"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44072"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103624"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of progressive shortness of breath. He has had a fever, painful knees and ankles, and generalised fatigue over the last week. Three weeks ago, he developed a sore throat that resolved spontaneously after a few days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with obvious facial swelling and bilateral ankle swelling. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 39.1\u00b0C. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESkin examination reveals a red macular rash on his trunk and upper arms, with a circular, well-demarcated border. It is not itchy or painful. Cardiac auscultation reveals a pansystolic murmur radiating to the axilla with an S3 gallop. Lung sounds reveal bilateral coarse crackles at the bases. The liver edge is palpable 4 cm below the costal margin. A chest X-ray shows cardiomegaly with pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Kawasaki disease","Viral myocarditis","Acute rheumatic fever","Infective endocarditis","Nephrotic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a recent streptococcal throat infection most likely from Group A Streptococcus, followed by the development of migratory polyarthritis, carditis (evidenced by a new murmur, S3 gallop, and heart failure), and the characteristic rash of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema marginatum\u003C/strong\u003E. This constellation of findings is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute rheumatic fever is an inflammatory sequela involving the joints, heart, skin and other organs that usually occurs two to four weeks after an untreated group A streptococcal pharyngitis. The pathophysiology is thought to be due to molecular mimicry between the streptococcal M protein and host cardiac myosin, triggering an autoimmune response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient meets three major Jones criteria \u2013 carditis, polyarthritis, and erythema marginatum. He also fulfils a minor criterion (fever). Two major manifestations and evidence of preceding Strep A infection is required for a diagnosis of acute rheumatic fever. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with heart failure and cardiomegaly, the absence of a preceding viral illness and presence of other characteristic findings of rheumatic fever make it less likely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lack of conjunctivitis, oropharyngeal changes, and cervical lymphadenopathy argue against \u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfective endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the patient\u0027s age and absence of risk factors like congenital heart disease or indwelling catheters. The rash and polyarthritis would also be atypical. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Enephrotic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oedema and dyspnea from hypoalbuminemia, it would not explain the fever, rash, or cardiac findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heart failure, fever, migratory polyarthritis, and erythema marginatum in a child points strongly towards a diagnosis of acute rheumatic fever following a recent streptococcal throat infection."],"references":["Parks T, Smeesters PR, Steer AC. Streptococcal skin infection and rheumatic heart disease. Curr Opin Infect Dis 2012;25:145. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22327467/","Gewitz MH, Baltimore RS, Tani LY, et al. Revision of the Jones Criteria for the diagnosis of acute rheumatic fever in the era of Doppler echocardiography: A scientific statement from the American Heart Association. Circulation 2015;131:1806. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25908771/","RHDAustralia (ARF/RHD writing group). The 2020 Australian guideline for prevention, diagnosis and management of acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease (3.2 edition, March 2022); 2020. Available from: https://www.rhdaustralia.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/arf_rhd_guidelines_3.2_edition_march_2022.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86041"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86041"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T21:08:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T21:09:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103624"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt"